---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import PageHeader from '../components/PageHeader.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Manifesto — notavibe"
  description="Open source is critical infrastructure maintained largely by unpaid individuals. We only fund the backbone after it snaps. This is why notavibe exists — and why this is not a vibe."
>
  <PageHeader
    kicker="// manifesto"
    title="The internet runs on people. Pay them."
  />

  <article class="section">
    <div class="container container--prose prose">
      <p class="lead-para">
        There is a cartoon that every engineer has seen. A towering, precarious structure labelled
        &ldquo;all modern digital infrastructure,&rdquo; and the whole thing is balanced on a single
        tiny block: &ldquo;a project some random person in Nebraska has been thanklessly maintaining
        since 2003.&rdquo; We laugh because it is true, and then we go back to importing the block.
      </p>

      <p>
        Open source is not a hobby that got lucky. It is the load-bearing wall of the modern economy.
        Researchers at Harvard Business School put a number on it in 2024: recreating the most widely
        used open source software from scratch would cost on the order of <strong>$8.8 trillion</strong>.
        That is the replacement cost of software the world uses for free &mdash; and that most of its
        authors maintain for free.
      </p>

      <h2>We only look up when the backbone cracks</h2>
      <p>
        In 2016, one developer unpublished an eleven-line package after a dispute, and builds broke
        across the industry. In 2014, Heartbleed exposed that a huge slice of the web&rsquo;s encryption
        was held together by essentially one funded developer. In 2021, a global security emergency
        &mdash; Log4Shell &mdash; landed on a logging library kept alive by a small volunteer team.
        In 2022, an exhausted maintainer deliberately broke their own popular libraries. In 2024, an
        attacker spent two years grooming the trust of one burned-out solo maintainer and nearly
        slipped a backdoor into the world&rsquo;s SSH servers.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every one of these became a headline. Every one of them was, underneath, the same story: a
        person carrying far more than one person should, with far less support than the work deserved.
        We notice the backbone only when it snaps. It should not take a CVE.
      </p>

      <h2>Gratitude is not a wage</h2>
      <p>
        The usual answer is a GitHub star, a thank-you in a changelog, a &ldquo;this is amazing, please
        never stop.&rdquo; Appreciation is lovely. It does not pay rent, and it does not buy the time
        that turns a stressed volunteer into a maintainer who can answer an issue the same day because
        it is now the job, not the guilt.
      </p>
      <p>
        Meanwhile the value is measurable and enormous. Two million downloads a week is not a vanity
        metric &mdash; it is two million weekly acts of dependence. When that number sits next to
        <strong>$0 a month</strong>, that is not a maintainer&rsquo;s failure. It is a market failure.
      </p>

      <h2>What we are, and what we refuse to be</h2>
      <p>
        notavibe connects the companies that depend on open source with the people who maintain it,
        and routes money to them <strong>matched to real usage</strong> &mdash; downloads, dependents,
        the funding gap &mdash; not to whoever markets themselves best. Solo and duo maintainers first,
        because they carry the most risk and receive the least.
      </p>
      <p>We are not a bulk-mail machine. We hold ourselves to a few hard lines:</p>
      <ul role="list">
        <li>We contact people only through channels they made public themselves, and every contact has a recorded source.</li>
        <li>We never harvest commit-log emails, never scrape browsers, never buy data from brokers.</li>
        <li>We honor an opt-out the same day, permanently. No dark patterns, ever.</li>
        <li>The money is the point. Maintainers keep the overwhelming majority; our fee is small and published.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>This is not a vibe</h2>
      <p>
        &ldquo;Supporting open source&rdquo; has become a vibe &mdash; a value companies profess and
        rarely fund, a feeling that evaporates the moment a budget line is needed. We took the opposite
        name on purpose. The claims on this site are numbers. The funding is real money to real people.
        The people are not abstractions; they are the reason your product works this morning.
      </p>
      <p>
        Fund the people behind the code. Not because it is charitable. Because it is true, it is
        overdue, and everything you ship is standing on them.
      </p>

      <p class="sig">This is not a vibe.</p>

      <p class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/#join">Claim your page</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/for-companies">Back a maintainer</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .lead-para { font-size: var(--fs-xl); line-height: 1.5; color: var(--text); }
  .prose h2 { color: var(--text-strong); }
  .sig {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--fs-h3);
    color: var(--ember-500);
    margin-top: var(--space-2xl) !important;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }
  .cta-row { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: var(--space-sm); margin-top: var(--space-lg) !important; }
</style>
